<font size=3D"3" face=3D"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><b>The right=20
            to choose =96 for farmers in Haiti: Anti-corporate activists
pervert=20
            =93social justice=94 and perpetuate poverty in Haiti - Paul
Driessen<br>
            </b>The Monsanto Company is learning a valuable lesson in
Haiti: no=20
            good deed goes unpunished at the hands of radical
anti-corporate elements=20
            of Western society.<br>
            <br>
            Like so many other concerned citizens, Monsanto responded to
the tragic=20
            January 12 earthquake that further devastated this
impoverished country.=20
            It worked for months with Haiti=92s Agricultural Ministry to
select=20
            seeds best suited to local climates, needs and practices, and
to handle=20
            the donation so as to support, rather than undermine, the
country=92s=20
            agricultural and economic infrastructure.<br>
            <br>
            From Monsanto=92s extensive inventory, they jointly chose
conventionally=20
            bred hybrid (not biotech / genetically modified / GM)
varieties of=20
            field corn and seven vegetables: cabbage, carrots, eggplants,
onions,=20
            tomatoes, spinach and melons. Instead of giving the seeds to
farmers,=20
            the company worked with the USAID-funded WINNER program, to
donate=20
            the seeds to stores owned and managed by Haitian farmer
associations.=20
            The 475 tons of hybrid seeds will then be sold to many
thousands of=20
            farmers at steep discounts, and all revenues will be
reinvested in=20
            local agriculture.<br>
            <br>
            Other companies and donors are providing fertilizers,
insecticide=20
            and herbicides that will likewise be sold at a discount. The
companies,=20
            Agricultural Ministry, farmers associations and other experts
will=20
            also provide technical advice and assistance =96 much as the
USDA=92s=20
            Cooperative Extension System does =96 on how, when and whether
to use=20
            the various hybrids, fertilizers, and weed and insect-control
chemicals.<br>
            <br>
            The goal is simple. Help get the country and its farmers back
on their=20
            feet, improve farming practices, crop yields and nutrition
levels,=20
            and increase incomes and living standards. <br>
            The reaction of anti-corporate activists was instantaneous,
intense,=20
            perverse, patronizing and hypocritical. Monsanto wants to
turn Haiti=20
            back into =93a slave colony,=94 ranted Organic Consumers
Association founder=20
            Ronnie Cummins. Hybrid and GM seeds will destroy our
diversity, small-farmer=20
            agriculture and =93what is left of our environment,=94 raged
Chavannes=20
            Jean-Baptiste, leader of the Peasant Movement of=20
Papaye.<br>
            <br>
            Other self-anointed =93peasant representatives=94 waded in. The
seeds=20
            are genetically modified and =93will exterminate our people.=94
Farmers=20
            won=92t be able to afford the seeds or feed their children. The
fertilizers=20
            are carcinogenic. Fungicides on the seeds are toxic poisons.
=93Seeds=20
            are the patrimony of humanity.=94 We support =93food and seed
sovereignty.=94Traditional=20
            seeds and farming practices =93provide stable employment=94 for
the 70%=20
            of Haitians who are small farmers. And of course, =93Down with
Monsanto.=94<br>
            <br>
            Various U.S. churches and foundations chimbed in.
=93Spontaneous=94 protests=20
            were organized in several Haitian and American cities. At
one, hundreds=20
            of marchers wore identical shirts and hats, which even at a
combined=20
            value of just $5 represented two weeks=92 income for average
Haitian=20
            farmers: 40 cents a day. One wonders how many would have
shown up=20
            without these inducements.<br>
            <br>
            Indeed, this abysmal income underscores the terrible reality
of life=20
            in this island nation, even before the earthquake, and the
perversity=20
            of this campaign against =93corporate control of the food
system.=94 Instead=20
            of =93seed sovereignty,=94 the activists are ensuring
eco-imperialism=20
            and poverty sovereignty. <br>
            Forty years ago, Haiti was largely self-sufficient in food
production=20
            and actually exported coffee, sugar and mangoes. Today, the
country=20
            imports 80% of its rice and 97% of the 31 million eggs it
consumes=20
            monthly. Two-thirds of Haiti=92s people are farmers (roughly
equivalent=20
            to the United States just after the Civil War), but their
crop yields=20
            are among the lowest in the Western Hemisphere.<br>
            <br>
            Few of Haiti=92s rural families have running water or
electricity, and=20
            women spend hours a day cooking over open fires. Many
contract serious=20
            lung diseases as a result, and life expectancy is twelve
years lower=20
            than for people on the Dominican Republic side of the
island.<br>
            <br>
            Google satellite images reveal a lush green eastern DR
two-thirds=20
            of Hispaniola =96 in stark contrast to the deforested, rutted,
brown,=20
            impoverished Haitian side, from which enormous quantities of
soil=20
            are washed into the ocean every year. Roads are so rutted and
awful=20
            that Peace Corps workers report traveling four hours by truck
to go=20
            60 miles. Many rural people cannot afford to feed their
children,=20
            leaving hundreds of kids in poor highland areas literally
starving=20
            to death.<br>
            <br>
            Hybrid seeds can help Haitians climb out of this morass.
They=92re no=20
            silver bullet, but they are one of the cheapest, easiest and
best=20
            investments a farmer can make. By simply planting different
seeds=20
            and adding fertilizer, farmers can dramatically increase crop
yields.=20
            A similar Monsanto donation of hybrid maize (corn) seeds and
fertilizer=20
            to Malawi farmers in 2006 generated a 500% increase in yields
and=20
            helped feed a million people for a year. <br>
            <br>
            In the United States, organic and conventional farmers alike
plant=20
            numerous hybrids. They cost more than traditional,
open-pollinated=20
            seeds, but the payoff in yield, revenue, and uniformity of
size, quality=20
            and ripening time makes the investment decision easy. Between
1933=20
            and 2000, U.S. corn yields likewise expanded fivefold =96
thanks to=20
            hybrids, fertilizer, irrigation and innovative crop
management practices=20
            =96 and today, hybrid or GM hybrid crops are planted on
virtually every=20
            American field. <br>
            Some of the Haitian corn donation will be used to improve
chicken=20
            farming and egg production. Most will likely be used in
staples like=20
            sauce pois =96 corn mush topped with black or red beans
combined with=20
            coconut milk, hot peppers, onions, garlic and oil. The
thickness of=20
            the bean sauce reflects a family=92s income, and =93wealthy=94
families=20
            often accompany the sauce with rice, instead of corn mush.
The veggie=20
            seeds will add variety to family diets, and provide a source
of income=20
            via sales at local markets. <br>
            <br>
            The hybrids will also help Haiti adopt truly sustainable
farming practices:=20
            higher crop yields, greater revenues and better nutrition for
more=20
            people, at lower cost, from less land, using less water and
fewer=20
            pesticides, requiring less time in fields, and enabling more
farmers=20
            to specialize in other trades and send their children to
school. In=20
            short, greater opportunity and prosperity for millions.=20
<br>
            And yet, activists continue to spew forth invective,
preposterous=20
            claims and disinformation =96 primarily through the Huffington
Post=20
            and several other websites. Hybrid seeds don=92t regenerate,
they assert;=20
            wrong =96 they do and can be replanted, though they will not
pass all=20
            their best traits down to subsequent generations, which is
one reason=20
            farmers typically buy new seeds. The seeds are poisonous,
they fume;=20
            false =96 the seeds are treated with fungicides that are used
safely=20
            all over the USA, Western Europe and Latin America, to keep
seeds=20
            from being destroyed by fungus before they germinate. <br>
            (For additional information and discussions, see plant
geneticist=20
            Anastasia Bodnar=92s Biofortified website.) <br>
            <br>
            Monsanto will not force farmers to plant hybrid seeds =96 or
say they=20
            can=92t replant what they collect from previous harvests.
Indeed, hybrids=20
            were widely just 30 years ago by Haitian farmers, who know
what they=20
            are looking for in a crop, how to assess what they have
planted and=20
            harvested, and whether they want to invest in specific seeds.
They=20
            should be allowed to make their own decisions =96 just as
others should=20
            be permitted to plant whatever traditional, heirloom or
open-pollinated=20
            seeds they wish. <br>
            <br>
            =93We reject Monsanto seeds,=94 say anti-hybrid activists. They
might,=20
            and that=92s fine. But thousands of other Haitian farmers want
to plant=20
            Monsanto seeds. Their right to choose must also be respected
=96 not=20
            denied by intolerant protesters, who are largely funded and
guided=20
            by well-fed First World campaigners. <br>
            <br>
            After years of vicious assaults by agro and eco purists,
Monsanto=92s=20
            corporate skin is probably thick enough to survive these lies
and=20
            often highly personal attacks. Other companies, however,
might lack=20
            the fortitude to provide their expertise and technology after
future=20
            disasters, in the face of such attacks. <br>
            That is almost certainly an objective for many of these
anti-technology,=20
            anti-corporate groups. Monsanto has no maize financial
interests in=20
            Haiti and only a tiny vegetable operation, and I have no
financial=20
            interest in Monsanto. But for the world=92s most destitute
people, it=20
            would be a tragedy of epic proportions. <br>
            See: <a
href=3D"http://www.canadafreepress.com/index.php/article/24193">http://www.=
canadafreepress.com/index.php/article/24193</a><br>
            <br>
            <br>
            Ma remarque (GW) : On voit bien ici que la &quot;droite&quot;
am=E9ricaine=20
            comme la &quot;droite&quot; fran=E7ais, est devenue technophile
(sauf=20
            des attard=E9s nostalgiques du &quot;La terre ne ment
pas&quot;, en=20
            m=EAme temps que la &quot;gauche&quot; est devenue largement
technophobe=20
            (sauf des attard=E9s qui restent dans la tradition des
Lumi=E8res).<br>
